{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
'''Francis James Patrick Lilley''' (24 July 1907 &ndash; 21 August 1971) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] civil engineering company chairman and politician.

==Military service==
Lilley was the son of Francis John Charles Lilley, who had founded F. J. C. Lilley Ltd, a [[Glasgow]]-based civil engineering company. He was educated at [[Bellahouston]] Academy, and worked for the family firm before joining the [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]] in 1934. However, he left the regiment in 1940 to return to Glasgow, where he joined the 12th Battalion of the City of Glasgow Home Guard on its establishment in 1941; he was promoted to Lieutenant-Colonel in 1942.

==Politics==
After the war Lilley became Managing Director of F. J. C. Lilley Ltd, who won several contracts of major importance. He was elected to [[Glasgow]] Corporation in 1957, and in 1959 was selected as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate to try to win back the [[Glasgow Kelvingrove (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Kelvingrove]] constituency which the party had lost at a byelection. He was narrowly successful in the [[United Kingdom general election, 1959|general election of that year]].

==Parliament==
On 9 November 1959, Lilley was one of four Scottish MPs on a [[British European Airways]] [[Vickers Viscount|Viscount]] which was involved in a near miss with a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Percival Pembroke|Pembroke]] transport. [[William Baxter (MP)|William Baxter]], one of the others, said that he "got quite a fright". In 1960, he was made [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Richard Wood, Baron Holderness|Richard Wood]], then the Minister of Power and later Minister of Pensions and National Insurance.

==Later life==
Lilley lost his marginal seat at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1964|1964 general election]], and returned to business. He gave up as Managing Director of F. J. C. Lilley Ltd in March 1969 but stayed on as Chairman until his death.

==References==
